.01). While the effect size might appear small, in a contested election this change in support for a political party might alternate electoral results. Moreover, internet-based experiments commonly underestimate treatment effects, which appear to be larger using alternative methods. 60 Figure 5. Corruption treatment and the party expected to win the next Election. Note: General sample, binary data, t-test, 90% confidence interval. Corruption treatment and the party expected to win the next Election. Note: General sample, binary data, t-test, 90% confidence interval. There is also some decrease in the expected electoral success of Fidesz (0.652 versus 0.687, p=0.12). Hence voters exposed to corruption treatment were more likely to believe that Fidesz would lose the next election (although the effect is not statistically significant), which is consistent with the earlier finding on the negative impact of the treatment on Fidesz support (see Figure 4). Voters who were in the treatment group were also significantly more likely to believe that Jobbik will win the next election (even if my treatment never explicitly mentioned or referenced Jobbik). Notice also that the effects of my treatment on support for remaining parties are negligible (0.012 versus 0.008, p=0.26 for the green LMP, and 0.129 versus 0.133, p=0.43 for “Other” party respectively). In this sense, it is plausible to conclude that Jobbik, as the party that actively politicizes the anti-establishment agenda, allows respondents to express a protest vote when they perceive political corruption as increasing. Overall, the results of my experiment are in line with my theoretical expectations. I find that the increase in the perceived corruption of the political establishment significantly increased electoral abstention, decreased support for the incumbent party, Fidesz, and also increased the belief that the anti-establishment Jobbik party will win the next Hungarian election among the respondents. The latter finding may be indicative of the preferences of respondents who are undecided or not willing to directly reveal their voting intentions and it suggests that the ability of Hungary’s parties to draw attention to corruption scandals in the future might alternate the country’s political landscape. In November 2017 I ran an internet-based experimental survey in Hungary of a total size of 1010 participants (505 respondents for treatment and control groups respectively). The subjects were randomly recruited from a representative sample of Hungary’s population by professional polling company, Solid Data. The administered treatment primed respondents about the corruption of Hungary’s political establishment. The treated group was shown a video resembling a Hungarian cable TV news broadcast. The host in the studio showed several pictures presented as results of (real) Hungarian surveys, which demonstrated that the majority of Hungarians viewed the level of corruption of the political establishment as high and the ruling Fidesz party as just as corrupt as the MSZP, which was in power until 2010 (see Appendix I). The video also contained two street interviews with “ordinary Hungarians” (played by professional actors) who complained about the corruption of Hungarian politicians. The video referenced politicians belonging to Hungary’s major political parties–the right-wing Fidesz and the left-wing MSZP, the only two parties to rule the country following Hungary’s democratic transition. The video presented both establishment Fidesz and MSZP as equally corrupt but did not mention Jobbik or any other Hungarian party. The control group was shown a video of neutral content Figure 3. Figure 3. Examples of information provided in the treatment group video. Note: The inscription before the video said_ now let's look at the video below. After watching this video, please answer the questions. Examples of information provided in the treatment group video. Note: The inscription before the video said_ now let's look at the video below. After watching this video, please answer the questions. For the purposes of my experiment, I have included a manipulation check, asking the respondents what they thought about the corruption of two establishment parties, Fidesz and MSZP. In line with the information presented to the treatment group, my expectation was that treatment exposure will increase respondents’ belief that both mainstream parties are equally very corrupt. What do you think about the corruption of Fidesz and MSZP parties? Both are equally somewhat corruptBoth are equally very corruptFidesz is more corrupt than MSZPMSZP is more corrupt than FideszBoth parties are likely not corrupt Both are equally somewhat corrupt Both are equally very corrupt Fidesz is more corrupt than MSZP MSZP is more corrupt than Fidesz Both parties are likely not corrupt I used several specifications of my dependent variables. To address Hypothesis I, the question asked whether the respondents were inclined to participate in the upcoming election: Would you participate in the national elections to Hungarian Parliament if they took place this Sunday? YesNoI don’t know Yes No I don’t know To address Hypothesis II and III, the next question asked about respondents’ vote preferences. For simplicity, only the major parties represented in the Hungarian parliament at the time of the survey were directly referenced in the question, while respondents who wished to name smaller parties were provided with the option “Other”. Which Party would you vote for if the national election took place this Sunday? AbstainFidesz, Hungarian Civic AllianceJobbik, Movement for Better HungaryMSzP, Hungarian Socialist PartyLMP, Politics Can Be DifferentOther Abstain Fidesz, Hungarian Civic Alliance Jobbik, Movement for Better Hungary MSzP, Hungarian Socialist Party LMP, Politics Can Be Different Other An alternative (less direct) way of asking respondents about their voting intentions is by asking about their voting expectations. Respondents often forecast which party will win a given election with a remarkable degree of accuracy. 55 Such forecasts usually are even better at identifying the winning party than direct voting intention polls. 56 For example, on a national-level, survey data collected before seven US presidential elections 1988–2012, Graefe found that citizen forecasts are better than any other approach at forecasting both election winners and their vote shares. 57 Similarly, Murr et al. who used national-level data before each of the 18 British general elections 1950–2015 found that citizen forecasts are better than voter intentions at forecasting both the winning party and its seat share. 58 Two reasons may account for this phenomenon. Firstly, expectations tend to incorporate more information than intentions as they capture information about one’s own and other people’s voting preferences, along with the information from other sources. Secondly, expectation forecasts include responses from people who do not vote, who are still undecided, and do not wish to reveal for whom they will vote. 59 In particular, this formulation would allow respondents to express their preferences for Jobbik in a less direct way. The last consideration makes it a particularly applicable framework for measuring respondents’ preferences for the anti-establishment parties, since such parties commonly combine anti-establishment rhetoric with extremist positions on other issues. It allows respondents who would otherwise be reluctant to expose their support for such parties, to preserve confidentiality and anonymity while reporting their voting intentions. Which party do you think would win (if the national elections took place next Sunday)? Fidesz, Hungarian Civic AllianceJobbik, Movement for Better HungaryMSzP, Hungarian Socialist PartyPolitics Can Be Different, LMPOther Fidesz, Hungarian Civic Alliance Jobbik, Movement for Better Hungary MSzP, Hungarian Socialist Party Politics Can Be Different, LMP Other The results of analysis are presented in the following section. Formed in 2003, Jobbik managed to win over almost one million Hungarian voters in 2010 election, doubling the number that voted for the party to the European Parliament in 2009. In the subsequent national parliamentary elections of 2014 and 2018, Jobbik received 20.2% and 19.1% of the vote respectively. Since 2014 Jobbik has become the third political power in the country. The anti-establishment nature of Jobbik is manifested through consistent references to the divide between allegedly corrupt political elites and “ordinary people” in its rhetoric. From the start of its campaign, Jobbik sought to create a rift between the mainstream parties and voters by arguing that opportunism, lies and corruption were rampant in Hungary’s national politics. 44 Figure 2 pictures the salience of anti-establishment and anti-elite discourse for main Hungarian parties using the available evidence from the Chapel Hill dataset for the years of 2014 and 2017. It is a continuous variable with a value of “0” corresponding to the minimal importance of anti-establishment and anti-elite rhetoric, and “10” corresponding to extreme importance of anti-establishment rhetoric. 45 Figure 2 demonstrates that throughout this period the salience of anti-establishment rhetoric was much higher for Jobbik compared to other Hungarian political parties. Figure 2. Salience of anti-establishment and anti-elite rhetoric for political Parties in Hungary. Note: Chapel Hill Dataset, 2014 and 2017. Salience of anti-establishment and anti-elite rhetoric for political Parties in Hungary. Note: Chapel Hill Dataset, 2014 and 2017. In its manifestos, Jobbik repeatedly used the term “criminal politicians” to denounce the Hungarian political establishment for serving private interests and failing to respond to the popular demand for transparency. Jobbik's manifestos also hint at an existence of an illegitimate relationship between the political elites and private entrepreneurs during the privatization process and argue that political and economic crimes compromised the good of the Hungarian nation to the benefit of the corrupt elite. 46 To address this problem, Jobbik offers to remove Hungary’s current politicians, to put an end to criminality in politics, to reform the regulations of public procurement and to review all major state investment projects and past privatization deals. 47 Jobbik also offers to enhance the principle of accountability by lifting the immunity of MPs and introducing political crime as a new category. 48 While accusing all of the broadly defined elites of political corruption, the Jobbik party discourse tended to adjust specific targets of its political attacks depending on political context. For example, in its 2010 electoral campaign, Jobbik described both mainstream political parties as equally criminal: “Neither the political crimes of the carnation < the emblem of the MSZP>, nor the orange < the emblem of Fidesz> … can continue to remain unanswered any longer”. 49 However, at the time, the specific target of its attack was the then-incumbent left MSZP party, which by 2010 became involved in a number of corruption scandals. 50 Following the 2010 election, Jobbik entered the Hungarian Parliament. To maintain credibility among its supporters, the party now consistently needed to furnish proof that it did not belong to the “corrupt elite”. To achieve this goal, Jobbik leaders concentrated on directly attacking the incumbent Fidesz party and focusing attention on corruption scandals around it. 51 The salience of the issue of corruption for the Jobbik party grew over the years. As the ruling party, Fidesz, which flirted with nativist and anti-immigration sentiments, moved ideologically closer to Jobbik, the latter still preserved the comparative advantage of representing the largely untainted anti-establishment platform. After 2014, in an effort to move away from 