king these citizens less likely to partake in the democratic process. 23 Citizens who perceive corruption as increasing tend to abstain from voting in varying regional contexts as different as Mexico, 24 Latin American democracies 25 and non-democratic countries. 26 While the impact of political corruption scandals on voter turnout is less pronounced in more stable Western democracies, 27 in less established Eastern European democracies where parties are not well rooted in society and the public lacks experience with democratic procedures to hold the ruling elite accountable, voting abstention may be a more attractive and costless choice for citizens. 28 Hence, I hypothesize that voters who perceive a high level of political corruption may become more inclined to abstain from participating in elections. Hypothesis I: Respondents who perceive the level of political corruption as high are more likely to abstain from voting. Hypothesis I: Respondents who perceive the level of political corruption as high are more likely to abstain from voting. Secondly, while perceptions of corruption may make some voters “exit the system” (abstain from voting), they may mobilize others to vote against the corrupt elites. Kostadinova finds that while perceptions of widespread corruption discourage some voters in post-Communist countries, they mobilize others to “voice” their discontent. 29 Citizens who cannot trust their national representatives because they demand bribes have fewer incentives to interact with their elected politicians. The information about political corruption may thus decrease support of incumbent politicians. Scholars link perceived corruption and the politicization of corruption to anti-incumbent voting. 30 This also holds true in volatile party systems of Eastern Europe, where protest voting to punish unpopular incumbents has been a widespread practice. 31 In line with the previous reasoning, I theorize that perceptions of political corruption have negative impact on support for the ruling parties. Hence my first theoretical expectation is that: Hypothesis II: Respondents who view the level of political corruption as high are less likely to support the incumbent political party. Hypothesis II: Respondents who view the level of political corruption as high are less likely to support the incumbent political party. While perceived political corruption may decrease support for allegedly corrupt incumbents, it may also make voters more likely to support opposition parties that politicize the issue of political corruption. In fact, Davis et al. argue that perceptions of corruption can play a key role in the decision of government supporters to switch to another party. 32 Aderberg argues that voters punish political corruption when a clean political alternative exists; otherwise they are more likely to tolerate an allegedly corrupt candidate. 33 Which parties are such voters more likely to support? One particular group of parties that tends to benefit from politicization of corruption are anti-establishment parties. 34 Parties engaging in anti-establishment rhetoric explicitly identify with “ordinary people” and contrast themselves against a separate and coherent “political class” that is composed of all political opponents undifferentiated by party affiliation and may also include economic, intellectual and/or international elites. 35 These parties emphasize a fundamental divide between the people and the political establishment and see themselves as challengers to the ruling elites. 36 The use of anti-corruption slogans is directly linked to the anti-establishment nature of these parties. Emphasizing “corruption” serves these parties as the main vehicle to frame the political world in dualist terms–the “good” people against the “bad” elite and helps benefit from the loss in trust in political establishment. 37 Not surprisingly, rising corruption is the most common driver of the breakthrough of anti-establishment parties, albeit 