abstract={A growing number of scholars have documented how social identities defined by an attachment to place influence individuals' understandings about political power and representation. Drawing on this theoretical framework, we explore how place-based identities matter forAmerican federalism by documenting how attachments to the American states alter individuals' decisions to leave, or exit, as well as to welcome newcomers into their local communities. Using a set of conjoint experiments designed to measure individual attitudes about place, politics, and America's federal polity, we find evidence that Americans hold deep and consequential attitudes about the places in which they live. Our evidence confirms that state identities are still highly relevant in shaping American federalism and the competitive pressures between intergovernmental jurisdictions. While federalism may encourage individuals to leave, federalism also nourishes place-specific attachments, motivating people to stay. © 2020 The Author(s).},
